Exploring Different Types of Machine Learning Classification Algorithms for Predicting Song Genres¶

Why is this relevant?¶

For those of you who have used spotify for a while, I am sure you have noticed the buff in the song recomendation system. Recomender systems are used in all aspects of our lives, from the ads we get on instagram to the information in the spam emails I'm sure many of you get. The real spotify recomendation system is based on not only the properties of songs but also your history of songs listened to and especially the history of songs listened to by users who listen to similar songs as you.

For the purpose of my tutorial I wanted to start exploring the minipulation of spotify data, more specifcally how well we could use the properties of a song to attempt to classify its genre. Of course there are many more factors that go into classifying a genre like the lyrics, the artist, and more. On top of this, songs are usually classified as multiple genre which makes tackling this problem technically a multi-labal classification problem.

The goal of my tutorial is to give a walkthrough of the data science pipeline, with emphesis on the difference between unsupervised learning and supervised learning models, while also introducing multi-label classification. Throughout my tutorial I try to use an assortment of popular tools in order to show you what else is out there.

I will be using a spotify dataset from kaggle that has nearly 100,000 songs from around 100 different genres

Gathering and Cleaning the Data¶

I will be using several popular libraries including pandas, numpy, seaborn, matplotlib for data preprocessing, formatting and visualization. We will then use sklearn and skmultilearn for machine learning exploration

Unsupervised Learning vs Supervised Learning¶

One of my main goals in this tutorial is to explore the difference between supervised and unsupervised learning models. When it comes down to it they are fundamentally different. Supervised learning is used for labeled datasets while unsupervised learing aims to find patterns and groups from unlabeled data. In general if you have labels you want to use supervised learning because the model will learn and adjust itself based on the labels it knows. In the context of my problem, predicting genre, an unsupervised learning approach would be to pretend I dont have genre labels given to me and see how well we can cluster songs based on their properties. Although this is less likely to work I find it an interesting experiment to do just to see what we come up with. On the other hand, supervised learning in our context would feed the physical properties of our songs and their corrospnding labels (genre) so that the model can learn over time.

Unsupervised Learning: KMeans¶

KMeans is an unsupervised learning algorithm from sci kit learn that I will be using for this tutorial. The KMeans algorithm tries to group similar items into K clusters based on the similarity of their features. It is easy to picture in two or three dimensions as the algoirthm selects clusters of data points near each other. Although we cannot picture it multi-dimensionally, the computer can still calculate it. There are several important properties of the KMeans algorithm that you should know as well. "n_clusters" or K which represents the number of clusters we want to find, "n_init" which is the number of times the algorithm runs with different starting cluster locations, "max_iter" which defines the maxiumum amount of iterations allowed to converge and select our clusters, and finally "random_state" which we just set to an arbitrary value in order to reproduce our results.

So lets start by creating our first KMeans model. Lets assume to start that we want to cluster our data into ten groups and see what it does. After assigning parameter values we need to fit the model to the data we want it to cluster. Our data we are using is the dataframe containing rows of song attributes with no name, artist, etc. We can access the labels attributes of the model simply as you see below. Labels returns a list the legnth of the dataframe and containing numbers 0 to (n_clusters-1) which represent the labels the model has assigned to each row of attributes.

In [71]:
initial_model = KMeans(
    init='random',
    n_clusters=10,
    n_init=10,
    max_iter=300,
    random_state=42
    )
initial_model.fit(phy_song_attrs)
labels = initial_model.labels_
print(labels)

This result is definitely not great in terms of fitting the songs to genres. However, before we move on we should always try to adjust the paramters of the model in order to accomadate your data better and get the most accurate result you can. So how do we do this for KMeans? The answer is something called the elbow method. With the elbow method you plot the sums of the squared distances from each point to its assigned center, called distortions, for a range of different K (number of clusters) values. The point of inflection on the curve is the value of the best K value.

In [73]:
#lets use the elbow method to estimate number of clusters
maxk = 15
sse_vals = []
for k in range(1,maxk):
    model = KMeans(
    init='random',
    n_clusters=k,
    n_init=10,
    max_iter=300,
    random_state=42
    )
    model.fit(phy_song_attrs)
    sse_vals.append(model.inertia_)
    
sns.lineplot(data=sse_vals, x=range(1,maxk), y=sse_vals)
Out[73]:
<AxesSubplot: >

Supervised Learning: K Nearest Neighbors Classification¶

Now that we have explored the unsupervised learning algorithm, KMeans, lets talk about K Nearest Neighbors (KNN). A lot of people when they hear KMeans and KNN assume they are the same thing which is not true. KMeans as discussed before clusters unlabeled data according to its attributes. KNN on the other hand, because we use labels, uses the attributes of a song to classify it based on its K closest, already labeled, points. The tutorial here does a great job walking through and explaining KNN if you are interested. For now I will move onto implementing it.

Lets set up our data for the KNN classifier. Our independant variable, or X, will be the dataframe containing the numerical song attributes we are using to try to predict genre. Of course, our y or dependant variable would then be the corrosponding list of genres for each of these songs. You may notice that I am using the full dataset of songs here, not the ones with duplicates removed because now that we are using the genre labeling, throwing out data could mislead us.

Lets start by standardizing our data using sklearns StandardScalar(). This function allows us to standardize each column of the X dataset so that no feature exerts more numerical influence than another, that is of course unless we decided we wanted this to be the case. Next we can use sklearns train_test_split function to automatically divide our data into a test set and training set.

In [80]:

Looking through the differences between the three groups there are definitely genres that behave better or worse in certain groups. Whether this information is significant or not would require furthur exploration but for the point of this tutorial I want to move onto using multi-label classifcation

Supervised Learning: Multi-Label K Nearest Neighbors Classification¶

Up until this point we have been exploring relationships in our data but not using the correct method. In our KNN we are trying to guess a genre for a song that could actually have several genres. A normal KNN like that of which we used cant handle this properly. So I wanted to explore a type of machine learning algorithm that is admittedly new to me but a perfect fit for our data. Just as the name sounds multi-label classification(mlKNN) allows the model not only to predict one genre but rather several. In order to do this we have some more preprocessing steps we need to take. Right now each song entry is labeled with one of 114 different genres but what I want to do is condense this by making a new column, in my dataset with no duplicates, that will store all the genres for each song. From there I will need to one hot encode all the genres so that each genre is its own column with a value of 0 or 1 for each unique song because this is the way mlKNN takes in the Y or dependant variables.

In [88]:
duplicate = songs[songs.duplicated(['track_name'],keep = 'first')]
non_dup_songs = songs.drop_duplicates(['track_name'],keep = 'first')
#iterate through no duplicate df
new_genres = []
for index, row in non_dup_songs.iterrows():
    extra_genres=[row['track_genre']]
    name = non_dup_songs.loc[index,'track_name']
    #iterate through duplicate df and add genres
    dups = duplicate.loc[duplicate['track_name'] == name]
    for index2, row2 in dups.iterrows():
        extra_genres.append(row2['track_genre'])
   
    new_genres.append(list(set(extra_genres)))
    

non_dup_songs['new_genre'] =  new_genres     
non_dup_songs

As you can see we only had an accuracy of about one percent but this isnt suprising considering all the noise in the data.

Conclusion¶

From this project I have gained a lot of insight into the process of data science, especially the process of using machine learning algorithms. We covered various common preproccesing steps, various graphs and plots, and three different types of machine learning algorithms. Although we found we cannot predict genres well using these methods this information and all the information found throughout this tutorial teach us a lot about the process and an important fact about genres: they are more than just the attributes of a song. In reality, if we wanted to more accurately guess genres of a song I would probably use tf-idf and other natrual language processing techniques on the lyrics in addition to accounting for the artist, release date, and more.
